ked by a postcolonial, capitalist discourse of local markets, regional economies and national structures, which frequently emerge in local African settings but often originate in global and multinational markets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aMagic. 0aMedical anthropologyzGhanazDagomba. 0aMedical innovationsxEconomic aspectszGhanazDagomba. 0aMedical innovationsxSocial aspectszGhanazDagomba. 0aSocial change. 0aTraditional medicinezGhanazDagomba. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238873940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782388739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782388739/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK